[1] Laying hens, migrating cranes
Date: Sun 19 Dec 2021 17:38 IST
Source: Makor Rishon Daily [in Hebrew, trans., abridged, edited]
https://www.makorrishon.co.il/news/435425/


The Ministry of Agriculture announced today [19 Dec 2021] an unusual outbreak of bird flu in the locality of Margaliot [see map at <tinyurl.com/mtxksnbr>] in the Upper Galilee. Traffic restrictions on the entry of trucks and equipment into the poultry farms were imposed in the area, and anyone engaged with poultry elsewhere was instructed not to approach the coop complexes.

The Veterinary Services fear that they will have to prepare for the extermination of about half a million [240 000, according to other media reports] laying hens in order to prevent the spread of bird flu. The source of the disease is probably in the [migrating] cranes that brought the virus with them to the Hula valley [but see comment below]. Due to the avian influenza outbreak, the entrance of hikers to the Hula Lake Park [known in Hebrew as Agamon HaHula] and to the vicinity of the cranes has been closed.

This incident is accompanied by poultry mortality and requires culling and complete isolation until the event's termination is officially announced. This was informed to the owners of the poultry farms and the residents of [the regional Councils] Mevoot Hermon, Merom Hagalil and Ma'ale Yosef.

To prevent the spread of the disease, poultry breeders in the Upper Galilee have been instructed to refrain from reaching Margaliot in the coming days to prevent vehicles and trucks that had visited Margaliot, in particular those engaged in the supply of feed concentrates, from entering their premises, and to immediately notify any signs of disease or increased mortality among their birds. The Ministry of Agriculture also instructed the growers to refrain from allowing manure removal contractors to approach the poultry farms until the announcement of the event termination.

The source of the outbreak is said to be a disease event in the Hula Lake Park [Agamon; see map at <tinyurl.com/2p9fu9dp>], which started last weekend, where hundreds of cranes were affected by bird flu and many died. The management of the Agamon said that they are constantly in contact with the professionals in the Ministry of Health and the Ministry of Agriculture to find a solution to the issue [see comment below].

