******
[2] Laying hens, migrating cranes
Date: Sat 18 Dec 2021 08:52 IST
Source: Davar [in Hebrew, machine trans., edited]
https://www.davar1.co.il/350513/


The Ministry of Agriculture updated the Ministry of Health yesterday [Fri 17 Dec 2021] on dozens of cranes infected with bird flu that were discovered in the Hula Valley. The Ministry of Health asks not to approach the migratory birds and to avoid contact.

The initial suspicion arose following an abnormal mortality of cranes at the site. Following this, samples were collected by the Nature and Parks Authority and sent to the Veterinary Institute's laboratory at the Ministry of Agriculture's Veterinary Services, which showed that wild birds were infected with H5N1 bird flu due to widespread morbidity. The Ministry of Agriculture regularly updates the OIE (World Organization for Animal Health).

This case joins other recent cases in which H5N1 avian influenza has been identified in wild birds. According to a report published by the (acting) Director of Veterinary Services, Dr. Tamir Goshen, many cases of wild bird disease have been diagnosed recently in several places in the country, including Moshav Hayogev in the Jezreel Valley, Agmon Hahula, Kibbutz Migdal Oz in Gush Etzion and Kibbutz Mishmar Hasharon in the Hefer Valley. The current outbreak was detected in wild birds a few weeks ago, and so far has been diagnosed in cranes, pelicans and marbled ducks.

The Ministry of Agriculture also said that all avian influenza events this year [2021], as well as the current one, involved an H5N1 virus that could cause a low risk of human disease. This case joins other recent cases in which H5N1 bird flu has been identified on [5] poultry farms in Kfar Baruch, Kibbutz Ein Tzurim, Avigdor, Maayan Zvi and Nahalal. These events have been long resolved.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The distance between Margaliot (adjacent to the Lebanese border) and the Agamon, on its southeast, is 13.20 km (8.20 mi).

The route and direction of introduction of the HPAI H5N1 into Israel and into the poultry farms (hen-to-crane or rather vice versa), and the reason(s) of the severe disease, including mass mortality among the cranes, an event not seen before in a location visited by 5-digit number of migrating cranes each November, are yet to be investigated and clarified. One hypothesis could be the cranes' possible susceptibility, becoming infected in this bird-crowded meeting site from co-visiting infected migrating waterbirds of the order Anseriformes, the latter known to remain subclinical while infective. A One Health approach, incorporating animal health, public health, and ornithologists, is warranted.

The Hula Valley is an agricultural region in northern Israel with abundant fresh water, which used to be Lake Hula, prior to its draining. Lake Hula and the marshland surrounding it were a breeding ground for mosquitoes carrying malaria, and so were drained in the 1950s. A small section of the valley was later re-flooded in an attempt to revive a nearly extinct ecosystem.

Hula Lake Park, known in Hebrew as Agamon HaHula, is located in the southern part of the Hula Valley. The new site has become the 2nd home for many thousands of migrating birds in the autumn and spring. The lake covers an area of one square kilometer, interspersed with islands that serve as protected bird nesting sites. It has become a major stopover for migrating birds flying from Europe to Africa and back, and also a major birdwatching site. In 2011, Israeli ornithologists confirmed that Lake Hula is the stopover point for tens of thousands of cranes migrating from Finland to Ethiopia every winter. In Israel, farmers set out food for them to keep them from damaging crops near the lake. This likely has contributed to increased density.

A 2.51-minute video clip presenting the event in the Agamon is available at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a0QrhaM6X6I (Israel TV, Channel 11 News, 19 Dec 2021; presenter/commentator, Ruby Hammerschlag; in Hebrew). At the beginning, neurological clinical signs in an affected crane are presented. For a picture showing supernatant dead cranes in the Agamon (Hula Lake), see <tinyurl.com/3k24khww>. - Mod.AS]

[The affected birds are very likely common cranes (_Grus grus_). This species breeds in the northern parts of Europe and across the Palearctic to Siberia. In the boreal spring, these cranes embark on a long migration southward. Most eastern common cranes winter in the river valleys of Sudan, Ethiopia, Tunisia, and Eritrea with smaller numbers in Turkey, northern Israel, Iraq, and parts of Iran. - Mod.PMB

ProMED map:
Hazafon, Israel: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=8700388,1759]
